How the TeamCity Localization Plugin Works

The TeamCity-localization plugin is a server-side TeamCity 2025.11 plugin written in Kotlin 2.x on JVM 21. However, the actual translation work happens entirely in the browser rather than on the server.

The server’s responsibility is intentionally minimal: it injects a translation bundle and a lightweight JavaScript runtime into every TeamCity page. The browser-side script then rewrites English UI text in the DOM into Chinese dynamically at runtime.

Effectively, the plugin acts as a skin-level localization layer on top of TeamCity, deliberately bypassing TeamCity’s native i18n/resource-bundle infrastructure.

Injection into Every Page

LocalizationPageExtension registers a global page extension that injects localization.jsp into the <head> section of every TeamCity page.

The JSP performs two tasks:

It writes runtime configuration into window.__TC_LOCALIZATION__, including:
the active locale,
the translation API endpoint,
and the endpoint used to report untranslated strings.
It loads localization.js, the browser-side translation engine.
Translation Bundle Delivery

When the client starts, it fetches a translation bundle from I18nController, exposed at:

GET /app/localization/{locale}.json

The controller reads and merges three property files from translations/zh_CN/:

exact.properties
prefix.properties
regex.properties

These files are combined into a single JSON payload so the browser only needs to make one request.

DOM Translation Engine

localization.js traverses the DOM and processes every text node using three matching strategies in a fixed order:

Exact match

If the text exactly matches a key in exact.properties, the entire string is replaced.

Prefix match

If the text starts with a key from prefix.properties, only the prefix is translated while preserving the remaining suffix. This is useful for dynamic content such as usernames or counters.

Regex match

Patterns defined in regex.properties handle structured strings using capture-group substitution, for example:

Build #N succeeded

To support dynamically rendered UI content — including AJAX updates, partial rerenders, expanding panels, and similar behaviors — the script installs a long-lived MutationObserver. Any newly inserted nodes are processed through the same exact → prefix → regex pipeline.

Skip Heuristics

Because translation operates directly on rendered text rather than message keys, localization.js contains several hard-coded heuristics designed to avoid mistranslating non-UI content.

The engine skips:

<input> and <textarea> values,
<code> and <pre> blocks,
build numbers,
project/build/agent/user names and related links,
elements containing data-test,
short 2–3 character abbreviations,
URLs,
email addresses,
file paths,
and sentences ending with a period.

These heuristics reduce the likelihood of corrupting identifiers, technical content, or user-generated data.

Recording Missing Strings

Whenever the engine encounters English text that does not match any translation rule, it batches those strings and sends them to:

POST /_record

LocalizationCsrfCheck explicitly exempts this endpoint from CSRF validation so the browser-side script can call it safely.

On the server side, the request is handled by TranslationRecorder, which:

maintains an in-memory ConcurrentHashMap-backed deduplication set (capped at 50,000 entries),

loads previously persisted entries from:

<TeamCity Data>/localization/pending.properties

on first use,

appends newly discovered keys (properly escaped and with empty values) into the same file under synchronization.

This workflow creates a self-feeding translation pipeline: real user activity continuously surfaces untranslated strings into pending.properties, where they can later be reviewed, translated manually, and promoted into the main translation rule sets.

Wiring and Dependency Injection

All plugin components are wired explicitly through constructor injection in:

META-INF/build-server-plugin-localization.xml

The main beans include:

LocalizationPageExtension
I18nController
LocalizationCsrfCheck
TranslationRecorder

The plugin does not use annotation scanning. The same XML file serves both as:

the TeamCity plugin descriptor,
and the Spring wiring configuration.
End-to-End Request Flow
A user opens any TeamCity page.
TeamCity renders the HTML and injects localization.jsp into <head> via LocalizationPageExtension.
The browser executes the JSP output, initializes window.__TC_LOCALIZATION__, and loads localization.js.
The script fetches /app/localization/zh_CN.json and caches the translation rule tables.
The current DOM is traversed and translated using the exact → prefix → regex pipeline, while applying skip heuristics.
A MutationObserver continuously processes newly inserted DOM nodes.
Untranslated strings are batched and POSTed to /_record.
TranslationRecorder appends those strings into pending.properties for later manual curation.
